(display: "Typewriter") <br> (b4r:"ridge","none")+(b4r-colour:white) [//What is orientalism?// A means of describing a set of phenomena related to the way Western societies and cultures have constructed an idealized vision of the Middle East and Asia. Orientalism is rooted in Western colonialism; with its fundamental purpose of creating Eastern societies as exotic backwards, or ultimately inferior. Essentially, with orientalism, it is not the Eastern individual who gets to define themselves; the West does this for them.](b4r:"ridge","none")+(b4r-colour:white) [Disney's 1992 animated feature //Aladdin// was among the most popular films of the year. Loosely based on a tale from the collection of stories titled [[//One Thousand and One Nights//->origin]], the animated film tells the "rags to riches" story of the adventures of protagonist, Aladdin. However, critics have long stated that the film continues Hollywood's [[legacy]] of depicting Arabs and Muslims as offensive caricatures. Further, critics argue that //Aladdin// serves to confirm rampant orientalism in Western film. Click [[here]] to learn more about these issues.] (align:"<==")[<img src="https://media3.giphy.com/media/iDU6OlrBJ7c3tRtm0b/giphy.gif?cid=6c09b9525htev1p0jwdwqqw69lc9nmjvx7j1lh3qv94vz0rz&rid=giphy.gif&ct=s" width="300" height="315">](b4r:"ridge","none")+(b4r-colour:white)[//Mulan// (1998) is widely known as a departure from typical Disney princess stories, and was seen by many critics as being a feminist film, very loosely based on the ancient Chinese heroine [[Hua Mulan]]. However, critics argue that the animated film is an example of [[orientalism->click]], as the Chinese setting is not culturally accurate. Further, the film contains many cultural stereotypes of Chinese people. Click [[this link]] to learn more about issues and why they are important.] <br> (align:"<==")[<img src= "https://i.makeagif.com/media/2-22-2019/jxwKsG.gif" width="350" height="177"/>] (b4r:"ridge","none")+(b4r-colour:white)[//One Thousand and One Nights// is a collection of Middle Eastern folk tales which included the story "Aladdin's Wonderul Lamp". It is important to note that this tale was not in the Arabic version of One Thousand and One Nights. This story in particular was added by French translator Antoine Galland, who had little to no knowledge on the Middle East (A fact he admitted himself). Due to this, it is fair to say that //Aladdin// has been rooted in orientalism since the story's creation. ](b4r:"ridge","none")+(b4r-colour:white)[//Aladdin// opens with "Arabian Nights", a musical number that describes the setting of the film; the fictional city of Agrabah. One of the main issues the film faced was controversy over the opening song, which contained offensive lyrics that were later changed. See the unedited version of "Arabian Nights" <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W0Pf3SL6GKs" style="text-decoration:bold; color:inherit;">here</a>. Further, Aghrabah itself can be seen as a salient example of orientalism and [[xenophobia]]. This city becomes a single identity of Middle Eastern culture, and this one depicition creates a single image for viewers to associate with the Middle East. Further, Agrabah is portrayed as dangerous and hostile; in the film, Jasmine almost loses her hand in the market, and Aladdin himself is threatened with beheading. Has Disney's portrayal of non-American cultures in their animated films influnced Westerners' racial [[sterotyping]] of these cultures?](b4r:"ridge","none")+(b4r-colour:white)[Another major issue with Disney's //Aladdin// is the way the characers are drawn and animated. Aladdin possesses Westernized features (ie, such as lighter skin), as well as a Westernized voice. Further, Jasmine and the Sultan, two supporting protagonists, possess lighter skin tones than the rest of the characters, as well as Western accents. Antagonist characters or impoverished characters, such as Jafar and the royal guards, have darker skin, thick accents, and large noses. This, alone, enforces the subtle midset that eurocentric/Western features are more "trustworthy" and "friendly". Taken together, these choices work to "other" those with traditional Middle Eastern features, and may even be a form of Western [[propaganda]].]<br> <img
